          <annotation encoding="application/x-tex" id="S2.p5.1.m1.1d">
           A
          </annotation>
         </semantics>
        </math>
        and trajectory
        <math alttext="B" class="ltx_Math" display="inline" id="S2.p5.1.m2.1">
         <semantics id="S2.p5.1.m2.1a">
          <mi id="S2.p5.1.m2.1.1" xref="S2.p5.1.m2.1.1.cmml">
           B
          </mi>
          <annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content" id="S2.p5.1.m2.1b">
           <ci id="S2.p5.1.m2.1.1.cmml" xref="S2.p5.1.m2.1.1">
            ùêµ
           </ci>
          </annotation-xml>
          <annotation encoding="application/x-llamapun" id="S2.p5.1.m2.1c">
           italic-B
          </annotation>
          <annotation encoding="application/x-tex" id="S2.p5.1.m2.1d">
           B
          </annotation>
         </semantics>
        </math>
        experience quasi-single field inflation respectively. As there are turnings of these trajectories, the analysis in
        <cite class="ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">
         <a class="ltx_ref" href="#bib.bib6" title="">
          Chen:2009we
         </a>
        </cite>
        can be applied here. The perturbations, especially non-Gaussianities in the isocurvature directions are projected onto the curvature direction, resulting in a correction to the power spectrum, and potentially large non-Gaussianities. As shown in
        <cite class="ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">
         <a class="ltx_ref" href="#bib.bib6" title="">
          Chen:2009we
         </a>
        </cite>
        , the amount of non-Gaussianity is of order
       </p>
